<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="42d39871-bda3-53c4-9484-f5567a0edc29" activityNameId="0944544c-bb22-5799-8340-cf46b90171e5" parentActivityId="41fd2293-e485-585b-a256-3ffba8188741" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">trinexapac-ethyl production</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">Cradle to gate. The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">Production of trinexapac-ethyl production including materials, energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of trinexapac-ethyl. Emissions are estimated. Energy consumptions, infrastructure and transports are calculated with standard values. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Trinexapac-ethyl is an organic substance with the CAS no.: 095266-40-3. It is called 'ethyl 4-[cyclopropyl(hydroxy)methylene]-3,5-dioxocyclohexanecarboxylate' under IUPAC naming and its molecular formula is: C13H16O5. It is solid under normal conditions of temperature and pressure as a white powder. It is modelled as a pure substance. Trinexapac-ethyl is a plant growth regulator for grain, grass and rape. There are no publicly available information about the consumption of this substance on industrial sites.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Unger T., (1996). Pesticide Synthesis Handbook, Noyes Publication.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chinese Patent (2006) Method for preparing trinexapac-ethyl. Patent number: CN100398508C</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chinese Patent (2015) Preparation method of trinexapac-ethyl and intermediate thereof. Patent number: CN105085270A</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Sauter H., Zeeh B., (2009): Plant Growth Regulators, in Ullmanns Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Weinheim, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59–67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="34dbbff8-88ce-11de-ad60-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">GLO</shortname>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Synthesis involves the production of diethyl maleate from maleic anhydride and ethanol and the formation of an intermediate from the reaction of the produced diethyl maleate with acetoacetic acid (proxy for acetoacetic ethyl ester) in an alkali environment. The intermediate is then cyclised by dehydrogenation before being reacted with a cyclic organic compound (cyclopropyl formyl chloride). Material inputs are modelled based on reaction chemistry with a yield of 95%. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">C4H2O3 + 2 C2H6O -&gt; C8H12O4 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">C8H12O4 + C6H10O3 -&gt;  C9H13O5 + C5H9O2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">C9H13O5 --&gt; C9H11O4 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">C9H11O4+C4H5OCl -&gt; C13H16O5+HCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">One intermediate had to be synthesised (cyclopropyl formyl chloride) from 1-methylcyclopropene and acetyl chloride:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">C4H6 + C2H3OCl --&gt; C4H5OCl + CH4</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Chinese Patent (2006) Method for preparing trinexapac-ethyl. Patent number: CN100398508C</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Chinese Patent (2015) Preparation method of trinexapac-ethyl and intermediate thereof. Patent number: CN105085270A</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Unger T., (1996). Pesticide Synthesis Handbook, Noyes Publication.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Sauter H., Zeeh B., (2009): Plant Growth Regulators, in Ullmanns Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Weinheim, Wiley-VCH.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2021-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true"/>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
